docs(install): Redundant platform-specific mention

I'm guessing this is a remnant from before it got it's own page.

docs(docker): Clarify container image install

Capturing my changes thus far while I go off to educate myself about rST/Sphinx refs vs
links. As such, this duplicates a reference link in a way I don't like:

    :ref:`Automating Downloads <guides/getting_started/automating_downloads:docker and
    unraid>`

If you want to fix that or are OK with the duplication, this should be ready to
go. Otherwise, I'll fix and force push once I've learned how to do this correctly.

A matter of opinion in this change, I did away with the tabbed GUI vs headless code
blocks and the separate CPU/GPU passthrough code blocks because I find comments in
example code to be more clear, more readable, and more approachable. This also has the
benefit of putting informative comments in the resulting user's configuration. For
example, imagine a user that learns only later that they require GPU passthrough, their
configuration is already ready to get them started. This comes at the cost some repeated
comments (`environment:` and `deploy:` for GPU passthrough) and the fancy Sphinx
highlighting of relevant lines. I think the trade-off is a net benefit for users.

issue.title: Reuse same TCP connection for downloads
issue.body:
TCP connection speeds tend to take a while to ramp up. Making separate connections for two downloads may be fine for slower connections where it doesn't make a difference, but on fast connections a lot of time is wasted on waiting the speed to ramp up.
Reusing a connection (or multiple connections, see #58) would make this problem go away as it would only ramp up once for all downloads.

issue.title: Feature Request: Support Azure AD (RBAC) Authentication Instead of Admin Keys
issue.body:
First, thanks for maintaining this helpful tool — it's been a great starting point for automating Azure Cognitive Search index backup/restore scenarios.

Feature Request:
Right now, the tool requires the use of admin keys (SourceAdminKey, TargetAdminKey) to authenticate with the source and target Azure Search services. This approach works fine for prototyping, but it presents some concerns for production environments, including:

* Security risks from static keys being embedded in images or configs
* Secret rotation overhead
* Limited auditing or scoping compared to managed identities / service principals

It would be much safer and more enterprise-ready to support Azure AD-based authentication via DefaultAzureCredential (from the Azure.Identity package).

Proposed Change:
Add an option to authenticate using DefaultAzureCredential():

```
var credential = new DefaultAzureCredential();
var client = new SearchIndexClient(new Uri(endpoint), credential);

```
And either:
* Automatically detect if admin keys are present (fallback to key auth)
* Or toggle using an additional config flag like "UseAzureAD": true

This would allow:
* Support for Azure CLI login
* Managed Identity on VMs/AKS/App Services

Service Principals via environment variables

Use Case:
I’m running the tool in a Dockerized environment where I already have role-based access configured for my identity. I’d prefer not to handle static keys at all.

Thanks! 🙌

pull_request.title: feat(ux): show selected task details in Context panel
pull_request.body:
This commit implements the context panel feature.

When a user selects a task in the timeline or dependency graph, its details are now displayed in the right-hand "Context" panel.

Key features:
- **Task Selection:** Clicking a task in the timeline or graph selects it. The selection can be moved with the Up/Down arrow keys when the timeline or graph view has focus.
- **Context Panel Display:** The context panel shows the selected task's name, ID, duration, dependencies, slack, CPM timings (ES, EF, LS, LF), and critical status.
- **Task Actions:** The panel includes buttons to Edit, Duplicate, Deactivate/Activate, and Delete the selected task.
- **Keyboard Navigation:** Pressing 'Enter' on a selected task moves focus to the context panel for improved accessibility.

issue.body:
### What type of request is this?

New tool idea

### Clear and concise description of the feature you are proposing

The Levenshtein distance is an indicator for how much a text differs from another text.
A Levenshtein distance calculator tool might be handy for developers, when they e.g. work on algorithms to identify text changes and want to test their examples.
See also: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levenshtein_distance

### Is their example of this tool in the wild?

Online examples:
https://planetcalc.com/1721/
https://phiresky.github.io/levenshtein-demo/

### Additional context

_No response_

- [x] Check the feature is not already implemented in the project.
- [x] Check that there isn't already an issue that request the same feature to avoid creating a duplicate.
- [x] Check that the feature can be implemented in a client side only app (IT-Tools is client side only, no server).
